data.name: ipv6 private
data.comment: These are various ipv6 networks that should not be routed on the Internet

data.name: internal server
data.comment: This host is used in examples and template objects

data.name: server on dmz
data.comment: This host is used in examples and template objects

data.name: all multicasts
data.comment:
224.0.0.0/4 - This block, formerly known as the Class D address
space, is allocated for use in IPv4 multicast address assignments.
The IANA guidelines for assignments from this space are described in
[RFC3171].

data.name: link-local
data.comment:
169.254.0.0/16 - This is the "link local" block.  It is allocated for
communication between hosts on a single link.  Hosts obtain these
addresses by auto-configuration, such as when a DHCP server may not
be found.

data.name: loopback-net
data.comment:
127.0.0.0/8 - This block is assigned for use as the Internet host
loopback address.  A datagram sent by a higher level protocol to an
address anywhere within this block should loop back inside the host.
This is ordinarily implemented using only 127.0.0.1/32 for loopback,
but no addresses within this block should ever appear on any network
anywhere [RFC1700, page 5].

data.name: net-10.0.0.0
data.comment:
10.0.0.0/8 - This block is set aside for use in private networks.
Its intended use is documented in [RFC1918].  Addresses within this
block should not appear on the public Internet.

data.name: net-172.16.0.0
data.comment:
172.16.0.0/12 - This block is set aside for use in private networks.
Its intended use is documented in [RFC1918].  Addresses within this
block should not appear on the public Internet.

data.name: net-192.168.0.0
data.comment:
192.168.0.0/16 - This block is set aside for use in private networks.
Its intended use is documented in [RFC1918].  Addresses within this
block should not appear on the public Internet.

data.name: test-net
data.comment:
192.0.2.0/24 - This block is assigned as "TEST-NET" for use in
documentation and example code.  It is often used in conjunction with
domain names example.com or example.net in vendor and protocol
documentation.  Addresses within this block should not appear on the
public Internet.

data.name: this-net
data.comment:
0.0.0.0/8 - Addresses in this block refer to source hosts on "this"
network.  Address 0.0.0.0/32 may be used as a source address for this
host on this network; other addresses within 0.0.0.0/8 may be used to
refer to specified hosts on this network [RFC1700, page 4].

data.name: net-192.168.1.0
data.comment: 192.168.1.0/24 - Address often used for home and small office networks.

data.name: net-192.168.2.0
data.comment: 192.168.2.0/24 - Address often used for home and small office networks.

data.name: experimental ipv6
data.comment:
RFC2928, RFC4773 

"The block of Sub-TLA IDs assigned to the IANA
(i.e., 2001:0000::/29 - 2001:01F8::/29) is for
assignment for testing and experimental usage to
support activities such as the 6bone, and
for new approaches like exchanges."  [RFC2928]

FTP data channel.

data.name: xmas scan - full
data.comment: This service object matches TCP packet with all six flags set.

data.name: xmas scan
data.comment: This service object matches TCP packet with flags FIN, PSH and URG set and other flags cleared. This is a  "christmas scan" as defined in snort rules. Nmap can generate this scan, too.

data.name: upnp-5431
data.comment: Although UPnP specification say it should use TCP port 5000, Linksys running Sveasoft firmware listens on port 5431

data.name: All TCP established
data.comment:
Some firewall platforms can match TCP packets with flags ACK or RST set; the option is usually called "established".

Note that you can use this object only in the policy rules of the firewall that supports this option.

If you need to match reply packets for a specific TCP service and wish to use option "established", make a copy of this object and set source port range to match the service.
